{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb21dbfb-cde3-4eb0-8b67-a3069605ec0e","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n### MSTest\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n### xUnit (v2)\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n// or for theories:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n### xUnit (v3)\nSame as v2, but also adds:\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason\")]\n[Fact(SkipWhen = typeof(SomeCondition))] // conditional skip\n```\n\n### NUnit\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n### TUnit\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\nAll frameworks **require** the reason string. The key difference is that xUnit embeds the skip in the test attribute itself (`Skip = \"...\"`), while the others use a separate attribute applied alongside `[TestMethod]`, `[Test]`, or `[Test]`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a3ba3484-9f9c-4d95-91b0-4a9ddd048fa6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct skip/ignore attributes for MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit test frameworks. Let me use the relevant skill for this.","outputTokens":295,"requestId":"082D:144FCD:C5B44F:E4EB89:69EAC2E2"},"id":"ebac46cb-fd42-461d-9cc2-c776f2af9cef","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:10:01.717Z","parentId":"65ce76c4-131e-4766-bc81-6fc3e1687411"}
